{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"332bed08-0b41-4c7f-9836-52b25610f678","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Collect a trace (30 seconds):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p $(pgrep -f dotnet) --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use a **sidecar** or `kubectl debug` with an ephemeral container.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over manual stop to avoid forgetting.\n- `dotnet-trace` has low overhead (~5%) and is safe for production use.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a09b5dec-56af-46ce-b7ab-13a31b30618d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll give a concise answer.","outputTokens":388},"id":"34b2b67d-bc74-4ca8-84eb-412813750351","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:47:49.902Z","parentId":"81880bbc-8e1f-4e03-97a0-4ea8f17f0fb7"}
